What does balanced even mean?! ⚖️
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
I have a lot of thoughts about eating “balanced” throughout the holidays —no big surprise there 😉. So, as we get into the meat of this holiday season, I wanted to set you up with some of my best nourishing nutrition strategies for the most wonderful time of the year. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The biggest pitfall that I see during the holiday months is creating “rules” for the season. Like… “I will not eat any sugar during the holidays” or… “I’ll just reset in January”. 😤
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Instead, how can you enjoy the bounty of the holidays while still keeping hold of your nutrition autonomy? Swipe for a few places to start!

Let’s make a Holly Jolly Hotty Toddy! I’m also here to share the best craft cocktail tip you never knew you needed.
.
Use jam.
.
Yup, there are incredible artisanal jam makers in the world like @fatcrowgourmet from Troy NY. They do the hard lifting, creating complex flavors in jam form, just like the complex infusions used for GREAT craft cocktails you just need to add the jam to booze and shake it up!
.
Holly Jolly Hotty Toddy
2 heaping tbsp @fatcrowgourmet Peach Cardamom Cobbler Jam
2 shots local whiskey
2 tbsp fresh lemon juice
Shake vigoursly in a cocktail shaker.
Make a brown sugar, cardamom rim for mugs. 
Pour hot earl grey tea (my preference but black tea will do) into mugs, top with peach cardamom whisky infusion. 
Garnish with lemon and cinnamon stick.
Have a holly jolly sipping party.
.
MOCKTAIL VERSION ALERT!
Honestly, this hot toddy is a fantastic mocktail, just eliminate the whiskey and swap in some fresh squeezed orange juice. Bam! Holly Jolly Mocktail Toddy!
.

Tuna Nicoise Toast, made with @VitalChoice Ventresca tuna when you want something fast and convenient but also blow your mind delicious. 

1 can Ventresca Tuna - the best tuna on the market IMHO
1/4 cup kalamata olives
1 tbsp Calabrian chili peppers
2 tsp dijon mustard
1 tbsp olive oil
2 hard-boiled eggs
cooked French green beans (add to the pot with the eggs, cook until tender)
fresh tarragon 
salt and pepper
sourdough toast (I used GF sourdough here)
garlic clove

In a small blender combine olives, chilis, dijon, and olive oil. Blend until spread-able.

Toast bread in pan with olive oil. Remove from heat and rub with garlic clove. Spread with kalamata mixture, top with cooked French green beans, pile on luscious tender Ventresca tuna, top with sliced egg, salt, pepper, and finely diced fresh tarragon.

The whole story:
If you’ve been following along on stories you know I’ve had a challenging few weeks, for those who have only caught glimpses, here is the whole story, cue opening dramatic saga music:
A few weeks ago I had a bad fall at home (construction woes), my foot got caught on a nail and I landed squarely on my elbow. 
I shattered my elbow which required surgery and lots of random screws and metal to put my elbow back together. I am now bionic.
Post-surgery, things got even more gnarly.
The surgery took twice as long as anticipated (4 hours), which turned out to be too long for my body to be under anesthesia. I struggled in recovery and was readmitted to the hospital a day later with something called Ileus. Ileus is a paralyzed bowel, post-surgery, and... well... it sucks.
Within a few hours, I was transferred to another hospital, with a fever, lower lung pneumonia, an NG tube, and all of the necessary monitoring and interventions for Ileus. 
I feel so grateful for many things including; wonderful hospital care, the best husband who was a fierce advocate with every medical decision, and a family full of love and endless support.
I am doing great now, better and better every day, accepting that my elbow is going to take time to truly heal, but so grateful to be over the scary stuff and back to work.
Lessons? plenty.
1. If you have surgery scheduled (specifically abdominal surgery where ileus is more common) chew gum as soon as possible after surgery to activate peristalsis and hopefully prevent ileus (wish I knew this).

The goal should always be to increase tolerance to food not remove food from the diet to manage symptoms. 
.
I see this mistake every single day in practice. Clients come to me after they’ve seen many doctors and nutritionists for a variety of gut symptoms and they are limited to eating 5-10 foods. Only. Ever. Seriously. A handful of foods. 
.
‼️Are their symptoms better? Nope 
‼️Is their life better? Definitely not. 
.
When clients work with me we are focused on healing gut imbalances so they can 👏🏻 EAT 👏🏻 ALL 👏🏻 THE 👏🏻 FOOD!! 
.
A sign of improved gut and digestive capacity is tolerating more food! (📣 for the people in the back 📣)
.
This takes time and patience but it is the best feeling ever when a client shares their food tolerance wins!
